TI  - LLM-AGR: Large Language Model Augmented Graph Representation Learning for Recommendation
PY  - 2025
JO  - Knowledge-Based Systems
DO  - 10.1016/j.knosys.2025.114791
AB  - Graph neural networks have demonstrated substantial improvements in recommendation through user-item interaction modeling, but face critical limitations. Existing graph-based methods rely solely on structural patterns in interaction data, neglecting semantic information and being susceptible to noisy implicit feedback that can mislead models. Recent studies have explored denoising techniques and semantic integration approaches, but struggle to align heterogeneous information sources and identify genuine user preferences amid noise. Large Language Models (LLMs) possess extensive knowledge and reasoning capabilities, yet their potential for improving graph-based recommendation remains underexplored. In this paper, we introduce LLM-AGR, a framework leveraging LLMs to improve denoising in graph-based recommendation while augmenting representations with semantic knowledge. Our approach seamlessly integrates semantic representation learning with collaborative filtering signals through a dual knowledge distillation mechanism that bridges the gap between LLM-generated embeddings and graph-based representations. To address the noise challenge, LLM-AGR incorporates an adaptive graph structure learning component that dynamically identifies and filters noisy interactions while preserving essential collaborative patterns. We further strengthen this mechanism with information bottleneck regularization that balances information preservation with noise reduction. Extensive experiments on real-world datasets demonstrate that LLM-AGR consistently outperforms state-of-the-art methods across various metrics, showing particular advantages in sparse and noisy scenarios where both semantic understanding and noise filtering are crucial. The code is available at https://github.com/zhaxinji/LLM-AGR. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.
