TI  - A method of ontology matching based on harmony search
PY  - 2020
JO  - Journal of Nonlinear and Convex Analysis
AB  - The problem of ontology heterogeneity has become a hot issue with the increase of the number of ontologies. To achieve the goal of semantic interoperability among heterogeneous ontologies, many researches on ontology matching as well as mapping and alignment have been carried out. However, some problems, such as how to improve the accuracy and efficiency of ontology matching method, have not been well solved. In this paper, a method called OM-HS (Ontology Matching based on Harmony Search) is proposed, in which ontology matching is treated as an iterative process of finding the best matching (i.e., maximum mappings) between ontologies. OM-HS takes as input two ontologies (source and target ontology), and creates mappings for the concept-pairs with similarities passed the given threshold. To solve the problem of a concept mapped with more than one concept, OM-HS finds out all the non-1-1 mappings, and creates the corresponding harmony memories for them, in which source concepts are used to label columns. Then, for each source concept, OM-HS creates a mapped concept set composed by the target concepts mapped to it. Finally, the candidate matchings extracted from non-1-1 mappings are transformed into harmonies, and an improved HS algorithm is carried out to find out the best matching between ontologies. Experimental results demonstrate that OM-HS performs well on the benchmark proposed by OAEI, as well as on the test data from the real world. © 2020 Yokohama Publications. All rights reserved.
