DO  - 10.1145/3764727.3764767
AB  - Cross-domain retrieval, reasoning, and analytics in enterprise information governance face critical challenges from heterogeneous data (e.g., documents, databases, images, videos), interdepartmental knowledge silos, and misalignment between structured rules and unstructured content. To address these issues, we propose AdaMKG, a context-aware multimodal knowledge graph framework for enterprise-level tasks across four modalities. AdaMKG integrates enterprise-specific knowledge graphs through dynamic contextual modeling, leveraging prompt engineering and model collaboration to project entities (e.g., organizations, employees, assets, events) and relations into a shared embedding space. This enables low-annotation semantic alignment across departments and modalities. The hybrid retrieval-reasoning architecture dynamically fuses relational paths with contextual embeddings, supporting seamless cross-domain operates such as interdepartmental document retrieval, multimodal data-driven compliance policy reasoning, and governance-oriented analytics. A lightweight variant further balances performance and efficiency, achieving over 95% of the full model's capability while reducing latency. Experimental results show that AdaMKG consistently outperforms representative open-source models, RAG frameworks, and cross-modal retrieval baselines on standard benchmarks (e.g., 11.2 over GPT-4o, 5.5 over Next-GPT and 4.97 over FILIP). By injecting fused multimodal evidence chains into large language models, AdaMKG enhances retrieval-augmented generation and interpretable multi-hop reasoning across fragmented domains, offering a promising solution for real-world enterprise applications requiring both accuracy and deployment flexibility. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
