AB  - This paper proposes an intelligent knowledge graph construction framework for disaster risk detection in power transmission grids by synergizing Large Language Models (LLMs) and Vision-Language Models (VLMs). Traditional manual methods struggle with inefficiency, incomplete coverage, and poor cross-modal alignment when integrating multi-source data (e.g., drone images, defect reports, SCADA measurements, GIS maps, and weather alerts). Our approach automates hazard identification by leveraging LLMs to extract structured entities (e.g., equipment failures, meteorological disasters) and their relationships from textual reports, while VLMs analyze visual data (e.g., infrared thermography) to detect physical anomalies like insulator cracks or vegetation encroachment. A dynamic knowledge fusion mechanism mitigates LLM hallucinations by probabilistically combining model predictions with existing knowledge graph confidence. Experiments demonstrate significant improvements, achieving 93.1% entity recognition accuracy, 88.7% relation extraction F1-score, and 79.2% cross-modal alignment success. The resulting knowledge graph effectively models complex risk pathways (e.g., typhoon-induced cascading failures) and enhances hazard detection, such as 95% accuracy for insulator flashover identification, providing robust support for disaster early warning and grid resilience. This framework addresses key challenges in multi-modal data fusion, automated knowledge extraction, and real-time risk assessment, offering a scalable solution for modern power system security. © COPYRIGHT SPIE.
