AB  - Cross-modal text-video retrieval faces significant challenges. Most existing methods focus on matching textual information with the visual content of videos and improve the retrieval performance by enhancing the textual data, and ignore the rich information of video frames. To address this issue, we propose a retrieval method which differs from traditional models that rely on complex cross-modal interactions to enhance the semantic fusion of text with video frames. We construct an external knowledge base using large language models (LLMs) to improve the semantic representation of video frames during training and testing, while optimizing knowledge exploitation. We implement a refined frame sampling and selection strategy is implemented to match frames to query semantics based on textual similarity. Using LLMs, we generate semantically rich video frames from different textual descriptions and embed them into the original frames, thereby extending the semantic coverage of the training data. A layered selection strategy with a hierarchical screening mechanism to minimize interference from non-target samples. Experiments on the MSRVTT, MSVD and LSMDC datasets show that our method significantly outperforms existing approaches in Recall@1, improving the efficiency and accuracy of cross-modal text-video retrieval. © 2025 ACM.
