AB  - The complex coupling characteristics and time-varying factors of the new power system have increased sharply, which puts forward higher requirements for the accuracy and rapidness of transient stability assessment (TSA). Deep learning provides new solutions to TSA problems, but the reliability of models requires more practical application. Therefore, an assessment framework based on the fusion of synchronization knowledge and spatial-temporal information is proposed to enhance the credibility of the results in terms of feature selection, embedded interpretability, and integrated knowledge. The theoretical mapping between electrical features and transient stability is first analyzed to guide model feature selection. Secondly, the synchronization phenomenon of the Kuramoto model is investigated, and the key parameter (coupling strength) is introduced into the topology representation of graph convolution neural network (GCN). On this basis, the Infor-GCN model is proposed for extracting spatial-temporal information and enhancing features by combining with the embedded interpretable Informer. Then, an output strategy is designed to provide stable results for different features and improve the model's reliability. Finally, a simulation example on an IEEE-68 bus system demonstrates the superiority of the proposed method in terms of accuracy and efficiency, as well as its strong generalization ability with new samples. © 2025 Power System Technology Press. All rights reserved.
