AB  - Modern machine learning (ML) models for malware detection offer high predictive power but often lack transparency, hindering trust and interpretability. Ontology-driven representation provides a formal, structured way to model malware behavior that is both machine-readable and human-interpretable. This research proposes a dynamic malware ontology leveraging standard vocabularies from Malware Attribute Enumeration and Characterization (MAEC) and Structured Threat Information Expression (STIX), aimed at capturing behavioral features extracted via dynamic analysis. The structured dataset resulting from the ontology will serve as input to Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) and DeepProbLog to produce explainable detection results. This work addresses key challenges in explainability, semantic representation, and robust malware classification, contributing a novel dataset, ontology, and interpretability framework for cybersecurity applications. © 2025 Copyright for this paper by its authors.
