PY  - 2024
JO  - 2024 5th International Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Computer Engineering, ICAICE 2024
DO  - 10.1109/icaice63571.2024.10863895
AB  - In the context of the big data era, knowledge graphs have become a repository for storing vast amounts of data, and knowledge graph question answering has emerged as a result. However, users are no longer satisfied with simple question-and-answer interactions focused on a single triple; instead, they are demanding more complex multi-hop question-and-answer capabilities. Currently, multi-hop question answering remains a significant challenge. At the same time, if we consider introducing large language models, issues such as poor interpretability and untraceable pathways may arise. To address the above issues, this paper proposes the FP-MHQA (FusionPath Multi-Hop Question Answering) method. Using pre-trained models for knowledge graph and question embedding, and employing GCN to achieve feature fusion of topic entities, knowledge graphs, and questions can guide the model to infer a better next step at each stage, ultimately leading to the correct answer. At the same time, path-based question answering can better achieve path reasoning tracking and has good interpretability. The experimental results indicate that the average accuracy of Hits@1 reaches 99.34% on the 1-hop, 2-hop, and 3-hop datasets of MetaQA, while the accuracy of Hits@1 on the WebQSP dataset is 72.87%. It has been proven that the FP-MHQA method is effective in multi-hop question answering tasks. © 2024 IEEE.
