PY  - 2024
JO  - 6th Edition of the International Conference on Advanced Aspects of Software Engineering, ICAASE 2024 - Proceedings
DO  - 10.1109/icaase64542.2024.10850980
AB  - Named Entity Recognition (NER) is a fundamental task in Natural Language Processing (NLP), playing a crucial role in Named Entity Disambiguation (NED), especially when dealing with short texts and queries. Accurate entity identification is essential before linking entities to their corresponding entries in Knowledge Graphs (KGs). This paper presents a novel approach to enhance NED performance in short texts by introducing BERT SocialNER2.0, a state-of-The-Art NER model, and integrating it with WeLink, an existing NED system optimized for such texts. Our research provides a comprehensive analysis of the impact of improved NER on NED performance, offering insights into optimizing entity recognition and subsequent linking within KGs. We evaluate our enhanced NED system on several bench-mark datasets, including QALD-5, QALD-7, QALD-8, QALD-9, and LC-QUAD. The results demonstrate consistent performance improvements in entity recognition across these datasets, with cascading benefits for NED tasks, achieving an average F-measure gain of 10% compared to state-of-The-Art systems. © 2024 IEEE.
