AB  - In the evolving landscape of computational sciences and interdisciplinary research, accurately comparing clauses within free trade agreements (FTAs) poses a formidable challenge. The legal language inherent to these documents is highly nuanced, context-dependent, and semantically intricate. Traditional clause comparison techniques-such as keyword matching, lexicon-based metrics, or syntactic rules-often fall short in capturing deep contextual relationships, overlook implicit legal meanings, and struggle to handle terminological variations across agreements. These limitations significantly impair the reliability of comparative legal analysis, hinder informed policymaking, and obstruct effective compliance monitoring. To address these challenges, a novel deep semantic model is proposed, integrating clause-level graphs with transformer-driven encoders in a unified architecture. The system leverages pre-trained language models to generate rich semantic embeddings of legal clauses and utilizes Multilateral Normative Integration Model (MNIM) to model inter-clause dependencies and structural relationships. This hybrid architecture enables our method to detect both overt and subtle semantic alignments, identify conceptual shifts, and measure clause similarity with high contextual awareness. Empirical evaluations conducted on a diverse and multilingual corpus of international FTAs demonstrate the effectiveness of our approach. The proposed method achieves up to 15% higher alignment accuracy and a 20% improvement in F1 score compared to traditional and state-of-the-art baselines. These advancements support scalable, high-precision alignment of legal texts, enabling practical applications in automated policy drafting, legal analytics, and international regulatory harmonization. By bridging the gap between domain-specific legal interpretation and cutting-edge semantic modeling, our framework contributes a powerful, interpretable tool that advances both computational legal studi
