PY  - 2025
JO  - 2025 6th International Conference on Data Intelligence and Cognitive Informatics, ICDICI 2025
DO  - 10.1109/icdici66477.2025.11135123
AB  - How to efficiently translate across modalities is an important challenge in the field of machine learning. Therefore, this study proposes an innovative algorithm based on the hybrid variational multi-modal framework (AMTAs) for the problem of automatic machine translation in cross-cultural multi-modal integration of film and television data. The core innovation of this study lies in the construction of a hybrid variational multi-modal translation framework. The algorithm adopts a three-level processing architecture: (1) The multimodal semantic matching layer realizes cross-modal feature alignment through the difference map generator. At the same time, the improved SimCSE model is used to calculate the cosine similarity. This can dynamically extract the semantic difference word set; (2) The hybrid variational inference layer introduces the K -component Gaussian mixture model. This model dynamically adjusts the contribution of each component through the conditional weight network. The weight calculation uses the Softmax normalized feed-forward neural network output; (3) The small sample optimization layer designs a negative sampling strategy based on contrastive learning. This strategy sets the InfoNCE loss function with a temperature coefficient 0.05. The experiment used 150,000 sentences of bilingual film and television corpus for verification. The results showed that in the metaphor recognition task, the algorithm's F1 value reached 77.2%, an increase of 13.1 % over the baseline model; the BLEU-4 score in the multi-modal translation task increased by 9.8 percentage points. These empirical results verify the effectiveness of the proposed algorithm. © 2025 IEEE.
