TI  - LEAF: Logic-Enhanced Adaptive Fusion for Large-Scale Ontology Alignment
PY  - 2025
JO  - 2025 IEEE Cyber Science and Technology Congress (CyberSciTech)
DO  - 10.1109/cyberscitech68397.2025.00058
AB  - Ontology alignment for large-scale, complex ontologies is a foundational yet challenging task, critical for data integration across diverse systems. Prevailing methods often struggle with balancing candidate generation quality and efficiency, effectively fusing heterogeneous information sources—a key challenge in indicator system fusion—and adapting to model-specific strengths. In addition, many deep learning approaches lack necessary interpretability, which limits their practical deployment in high-stakes domains. To address these challenges, we propose LEAF (Logic-Enhanced Adaptive Fusion), a novel, iterative alignment framework. LEAF introduces three core innovations: (1) a Progressive Expansion Recall strategy to ensure a high-quality candidate pool; (2) an interpretable Complementary Heterogeneous Matcher architecture that integrates deep semantic patterns with features from a semantically-decoupled topology model and an LLM-based logical reasoner; and (3) a Two-Level Adaptive Fusion mechanism inspired by meta-learning to intelligently combine matcher outputs. Evaluated on the highly demanding OAEI Anatomy benchmark, LEAF achieves a highly competitive F1-score of 0.883, demonstrating a strong and well-balanced performance with a Precision of 0.905 and a Recall of 0.863. Our work presents a new, effective paradigm for ontology alignment that successfully combines the feature engineering power of LLMs with a robust, interpretable, and adaptive discriminative framework.
