AB  - The extensive utilization of multimodal data within specialized fields has underscored the importance of achieving precise semantic alignment between images and textual information to improve the efficacy of AI-driven systems. While Multimodal Large Language Models demonstrate robust cross-modal semantic alignment on general-purpose datasets, their effectiveness markedly declines in domain-specific contexts due to the presence of specialized terminology and limited availability of annotated data. Current methodologies frequently depend on full-parameter fine-tuning or the integration of intricate interaction modules, approaches that are computationally intensive and susceptible to overfitting. To address these limitations, this study proposes a lightweight differential fusion approach. Instead of fine-tuning the foundational Large Language Models, the method leverages a Semantic Alignment Residual Corrector to generate differential similarity representations and applies a Reciprocal Rank Fusion technique to integrate retrieval outcomes from multiple sources. This framework substantially improves both the accuracy and robustness of cross-modal semantic alignment. Experimental results on the COCO 2017 dataset demonstrate that the proposed method consistently enhances cross-modal retrieval performance across diverse base models, while exhibiting considerable generalization ability and deployment flexibility. Therefore, this research provides an effective solution to cross-modal alignment challenges, especially in resource-constrained settings.
