PY  - 2025
JO  - 2025 IEEE International Conference on Metrology for eXtended Reality, Artificial Intelligence and Neural Engineering (MetroXRAINE)
DO  - 10.1109/metroxraine66377.2025.11340152
AB  - In the field of job ontologies, the interoperability between skill poses a significant challenge in the labor market, affecting job matching and workforce planning. This issue is particularly relevant to employment services for people with disabilities, where accurate matching of skills with job requirements is essential to promote Return To Work (RTW). To support this process, the Italian Rientr@ research project developed a Decision Support System (DSS) to assist individuals with disabilities in identifying suitable job opportunities, taking into account their skills and abilities. The DSS leverages the Occupational Information Network (O*NET), a U.S.-based occupational standard, to assess job compatibility by matching individual resources with occupational demands. However, to ensure its applicability and relevance in the Italian labor market, the Rientr@ ontology needs to be mapped onto a standardized European framework. In this context, the European Skills, Competences, Qualifications, and Occupations (ESCO) serves as the reference taxonomy for skills and occupations across Europe. Given the structural and semantic differences between these ontologies, direct mapping is not feasible, as it leads to mismatches, missing correspondences, and taxonomic inconsistencies. Traditional rule-based approaches are insufficient to address these discrepancies, necessitating more adaptive solutions. This study proposes a machine learning-based approach to ontology alignment using word embeddings techniques. A semantic similarity model was applied to over 49,000 O*NET-ESCO skill pairs, achieving a precision of 96.8% in expert-validated matches. Results show strong agreement between raters and confirm the feasibility of scalable, automated alignment. By improving ontology interoperability, this research contributes to AI-driven employment services and supports a more inclusive and accessible labor market.
