PY  - 2025
JO  - 2025 International Conference on Data Science and Intelligent Systems (DSIS)
DO  - 10.1109/dsis67228.2025.11390557
AB  - Multi-site magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) studies are significantly affected by site-specific biases arising from variations in scanners and imaging protocols across different sites, severely compromising the cross-site generalizability of deep learning models. To address this issue, this paper introduces a content-style disentanglement-based harmonization method for multi-site MRI data, which employs separate content and style encoders to disentangle anatomical content information from site-specific stylistic features. Furthermore, a Triplet Attention mechanism is integrated into the bottleneck layer of the content encoder to enhance the modeling of multidimensional dependencies within complex content structures. Experimental results on the IXI dataset demonstrate that, compared to baseline methods, our model achieves a 18.3% improvement in PSNR, a 13.3% increase in SSIM, and a 56.2% reduction in MSE on the HH-to-Guys harmonization task. It also exhibits consistently superior performance on the IOP-to-Guys harmonization task. Meanwhile, site classification experiments show that the SVM classification accuracy decreases from 90.0% to 48.3% after harmonization, indicating the effective removal of site-specific characteristics. Qualitative and quantitative results demonstrate that the proposed method successfully eliminates site-related biases while preserving fine anatomical structural details, offering an effective data harmonization solution for multi-site MRI studies.
