AB  - With the increasing penetration of nonlinear loads and distributed energy resources, harmonic distortion has become a critical challenge in modern distribution systems. The accurate localization of harmonic sources is crucial for maintaining power quality and enhancing grid reliability. To enable such localization, this paper presents a data-driven harmonic source localization simulation platform developed in Matlab. The platform comprises three primary components. The first component is a data preprocessing unit that integrates harmonic power flow computation and multi-order harmonic extraction using Fast Fourier Transform (FFT). The second is a localization algorithm module that employs Partial Least Squares (PLS) regression to identify the locations of harmonic sources and quantify their contributions based on measured voltage and current waveforms. The third is a visualization module that presents the localization results through tabular data and graphical outputs. The platform provides an effective tool for harmonic analysis, detection, and mitigation in smart distribution systems.
