AB  - The integration of diverse data sources, including satellite images and descriptive text annotations is becoming increasingly necessary for efficient environmental monitoring. Textual descriptions provide contextual and semantic details often missed by high-resolution satellite images of land cover, vegetation, water bodies, and urban areas. Therefore, the present work utilizes a cross-modal semantic alignment approach to rectify this gap, combining textual data and satellite images for improved understanding and decision-making. The proposed system uses DenseNet-121 to extract features from satellite images and a BERT-based text encoder to handle textual descriptions. The learnt representations are then harmonised using a global average pooling process and semantic congruence between the image and text domains is established through cross-modal alignment. By reducing modality disparities and improving robust feature matching, a Noise-Contrastive Estimation (NCE) loss function directs the training goal. The final output classifies the football court, whereas multimodal data alignment enhances interpretability have the accuracy of 96 % high compared to the existing and enables more reliable, context-aware environmental monitoring.
