AB  - With the rapid development of information technology, massive amounts of multimodal data such as text and images are continuously generated and accumulated at an unprecedented rate. Against this backdrop, how to accurately and efficiently obtain the information required by users from massive data through image-text retrieval has become a core challenge in the field of information retrieval. Existing retrieval models often only attempt to align retrievals within a single semantic space. In this case, the probability of incorrect retrieval increases with the growth of data volume. This paper proposes an alignment method called MPCL(Multi-Plane Contrastive Learning), which tries to project data into different query vectors through cross-attention, enabling data alignment in multiple semantic spaces, thereby greatly improving the accuracy of retrieval. Experimental results show that the retrieval performance of the model improves as the number of query vectors increases.
