PY  - 2025
JO  - 2025 IEEE 10th International Conference on Data Science in Cyberspace (DSC)
DO  - 10.1109/dsc67331.2025.00019
AB  - This article provides a systematic review of research advances in Temporal Knowledge Graph (TKG) reasoning. TKGs extend static knowledge graphs by incorporating timestamps into quadruples (head entity, relation, tail entity, time), enabling dynamic modeling of evolving knowledge. Focusing on two core tasks—interpolation reasoning (completing missing facts within known time intervals, i.e., Temporal Knowledge Graph Completion/TKGC) and extrapolation reasoning (predicting future events) — the work thoroughly analyzes three dominant methodological paradigms: 1) Representation learning approaches (e.g., models based on Graph Neural Networks/GNNs, Recurrent Neural Networks/RNNs, or Transformers) efficiently capture structural-temporal patterns using low-dimensional embeddings but generally lack interpretability; 2) Symbolic rule learning methods provide transparent reasoning paths yet struggle with complex temporal dynamics and sparse data; 3) Neuro-symbolic fusion techniques (including early fusion, late fusion, and iterative hybridization) combine neural network performance with symbolic rule interpretability to achieve a balance between both. Comparative analysis reveals critical challenges in the field: deep integration of causal modeling and interpretability, automated rule mining under sparse data conditions, multimodal and cross-domain knowledge fusion, and synergistic utilization of Large Language Models (LLMs). Future research should develop falsifiability-inspired frameworks to advance the dynamic equilibrium between reasoning capability and interpretability.
