JO  - 2025 IEEE Smart World Congress (SWC)
DO  - 10.1109/swc65939.2025.00168
AB  - Digital twin monitoring systems suffer from interpretability limitations that hinder adoption in safety-critical industrial applications. We present the first neuro-symbolic rule extraction framework that transforms CNN-LSTM predictions into human-readable logical rules for transparent digital twin decision-making. Our approach introduces two key technical contributions: (1) the TENSOR (Temporal and Event-based Neural-to-Symbolic Extraction of Rules) algorithm that identifies multivariate temporal patterns in sensor data and converts them into Prolog-style symbolic rules, and (2) the DRCM (Dual-factor Rule Confidence Metric) that balances statistical correlation with predictive accuracy for rule validation. The framework processes high-confidence neural predictions to extract interpretable conditions including threshold checks, gradient analysis, temporal patterns, and feature correlations. Evaluation on synthetic industrial sensor data demonstrates improved accuracy over CNN-LSTM baselines while maintaining strong recall performance. Human evaluation with industrial engineers shows substantially higher interpretability ratings for rule-based explanations compared to neural-only outputs. The extracted rules achieve high confidence scores and provide actionable insights for operators, enabling validation of system recommendations through transparent logical reasoning. While current validation relies on synthetic data, this work establishes a methodological foundation for explainable AI in digital twin applications.
