AB  - Understanding ambiguous language in context remains a major problem for Natural Language Processing (NLP). This article introduces a combination of symbols and neural language models for resolving issues of ambiguity in English text. BERT is used to identify contextual ambiguities, and T5 for solving those ambiguities using text, and a reasoning module based on ontologies and logic rules in Prologue is added for this purpose. An integration approach allows neural and symbolic elements to interact, leading to applying rules when the model's confidence in a decision decreases. Data from the Winograd Schema Challenge, SQuAD, SemEval and GLUE were used to train and test the model. We looked at the results using accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score, BLEU and ROUGE, along with having humans review the outcomes. Using the suggested approach, accuracy reached 98.5%, as well as BLEU and ROUGE-L scores of 82.5 and 87.2. The model can manage various language forms, particularly where negation or sarcasm is present, which provides a practical and clear strategy to solve ambiguity in natural language processing.
