AB  - The rapid development of Large Language Models (LLMs) has demonstrated remarkable capabilities in natural language understanding and generation. However, they often suffer from inherent limitations such as hallucination, lack of factual precision, and opaque reasoning processes. Knowledge Graphs (KGs), with their structured, explicit representation of facts, offer a potential remedy to these issues. Yet, the traditional methods of integrating KGs and LLMs are often unilateral, failing to leverage the synergistic potential between the two paradigms. To bridge this gap, this paper proposes a novel Mutual Reinforcement Framework (MRF) for collaborative optimization. The MRF establishes a closed-loop interaction where the LLM acts as a dynamic reasoner to enrich the KG with inferred knowledge and resolve semantic ambiguities, while the KG serves as a grounded verifier to enhance the LLM's factuality and interpretability. We instantiate this framework through two core modules: 1) KG-to-LLM Injection via Structured Prompting, which feeds relevant subgraphs into the LLM's context to guide its response generation, and 2) LLM-to-KG Augmentation via Logical Deduction, which employs the LLM to generate plausible knowledge tuples for KG completion. Extensive experiments on two downstream tasks — Knowledge-Guided QA and Factual Dialogue Generation — demonstrate that our MRF model significantly outperforms standalone LLMs and baseline fusion models in both accuracy and factual consistency. Furthermore, ablation studies confirm the critical contribution of each component within our framework. Our work illuminates a path towards more reliable and knowledgeable AI systems by fostering a symbiotic relationship between parametric and symbolic knowledge.
