DO  - 10.1109/icmoce64100.2025.11076808
AB  - The Sixth Generation (6G) wireless networks aim to enhance data transmission efficiency and reliability by adopting semantic communication, which prioritizes contextually relevant information over precise bit-level accuracy. This approach reduces bandwidth usage while preserving the intended meaning. This article presents a neuro-symbolic Artificial Intelligence (AI) based framework that integrates Logic Tensor Networks (LTNs) and Matrix Factorization (MF) to optimize the semantic encoding and decoding processes. By leveraging logical reasoning and shared knowledge, the proposed model efficiently reconstructs incomplete or distorted data, even in noisy transmission environments. Experimental evaluations, conducted across a range of Signal-to-Noise Ratios (SNRs), demonstrate the system’s robustness in maintaining semantic reliability. Specifically, for low SNR values, the system demonstrated a decline in performance, with F1 scores between 0.52 and 0.57. However, as the SNR increased, the system’s performance improved significantly, with the F1 score reaching up to 0.65, and recall values exceeding 0.78 for higher SNR levels. High specificity (0.96–0.97) across all the SNR values further emphasizes the system’s ability to filter out irrelevant content effectively. These findings indicate that the proposed model is adaptable, scalable, and capable of efficiently transmitting context-rich information, making it suitable for a wide range of next-generation applications.
