AB  - The upcoming sixth-generation (6 G) communication paradigm introduces Goal-Oriented Semantic Communication (GoSC), which redefines the communication process by focusing not on raw data transmission but on delivering semantically meaningful and task-relevant information. Unlike traditional Shannon-based models, GoSC aims to optimize communication efficiency, latency, and resource usage by transmitting only the essential information contributing to task performance. This paper outlines the theoretical foundations of GoSC, presents its system architecture enhanced by artificial intelligence (AI) and edge intelligence, and explores key application areas such as autonomous vehicles, e-health, industrial IoT, and immersive augmented/virtual reality. Moreover, it discusses significant challenges, including scalability, standardization, and privacy, and highlights future directions involving human-in-the-loop systems, neuro-symbolic AI, and goal-aware network control. The study concludes that GoSC is poised to become a cornerstone of humancentric, intelligent 6 G networks by enabling communication systems to understand and act upon meaning, not just data.
