AB  - Large Language Models (LLMs) have demonstrated remarkable capabilities in natural language understanding and generation, yet their applicability to Traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM) remains limited due to insufficient coverage of physiological knowledge and the high cost of updating domain-specific content. To address these challenges, we propose the TCM-PK-Model, a novel framework that integrates dynamic physiological knowledge graphs with LLMs. Our approach introduces a multi-granularity semantic abstraction strategy for index construction, enabling efficient summarization of entities, triples, and knowledge modules while preserving interpretability. During retrieval, we design a multi-perspective query mechanism that combines semantic similarity matching with triple-importance scoring, enhancing the accuracy and relevance of retrieved knowledge. For generation, we construct a high-quality TCM physiological question–answering dataset through LLM-based data augmentation and BM25-based filtering, and conduct full-parameter fine-tuning of the Qwen2.5-7B model to enrich its domain expertise. Experimental results demonstrate that our model significantly reduces hallucinations, improves factual consistency, and achieves notable gains in ROUGE and BLEU scores compared to baseline LLMs. This work provides a scalable pathway for integrating dynamic knowledge graphs with LLMs, advancing both the reliability and interpretability of AI-assisted physiological modeling in TCM.
