AB  - The article discusses how the Knowledge Graphs(KGs) technology can be applied to Large Language Models (LLMs) to tackle Advanced Persistent Threats (APT) in cybersecurity. A novel strategic framework, APT-ArgusQA , has been unveiled, which merges KGs with LLMs. APT-ArgusQA tackles the problems of "hallucination" and insufficient factual knowledge in LLMs in the APT domain by adopting Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) —— a method for constructing context from reliable knowledge sources and then generating a series of prompts from that context. APT-ArgusQA employs First and Second-Order RAG Enhancement strategies, enhancing the efficiency and accuracy of LLMs in the APT domain by integrating APT Knowledge Graph nodes, neighboring nodes, and relational information. It also demonstrates how to fine-tune pre-trained models provided by OpenAI to suit tasks in APT knowledge-based question answering. The effectiveness of the proposed method was validated through a series of experiments. The discussion revolved around the potential of KGs in continuously learning and adapting to new threats, as well as their prospects in improving the interpretability of decision-making in cybersecurity.
