AB  - Recommender systems are widely deployed in e-commerce and digital platforms, yet their precision often degrades in scenarios with sparse interactions, long-tail items, and cold-start entities. Pre-trained embeddings capture rich semantic priors from large-scale external corpora, while knowledge graphs (KGs) encode structured domain relationships. However, these two sources of information are typically used independently, limiting their potential benefits. This paper presents CEKG-Net, an integration framework that aligns pre-trained embeddings with domain knowledge graphs through lightweight adapters and a contrastive alignment objective. Community detection is incorporated to propagate collaborative preferences, and contextual encoders explicitly model seasonality, promotions, and demand shifts. Extensive experiments on RetailRocket and Taobao datasets demonstrate that CEKG-Net consistently outperforms state-of-the-art baselines such as BERT4Rec, KGAT, and LightGCN, achieving significant gains in NDCG@10, Recall@10, and MRR. The results highlight the effectiveness of combining semantic priors with structured knowledge for improving recommendation precision under real-world conditions, particularly for cold-start and long-tail items.
