AB  - Vocabulary acquisition is a task that depends on understanding the semantic relationships between words. Given the recent advances in large language models (LLMs) and their strong performance in natural language understanding, this paper explores the challenges of vocabulary acquisition for EAL (English as an Additional Language) learners and the potential role of LLMs in supporting it. We argue that while LLMs effectively capture general linguistic patterns, they lack explicit logical structure when analyzing learners’ cognitive skills, so LLMs can hardly offer personalized learning experiences. To help EAL learners, we propose a novel approach that integrates Non-Axiomatic Logic (NAL) with LLMs to support more personalized and structured vocabulary learning.
