PY  - 2025
JO  - 2025 Twelfth International Conference on Intelligent Computing and Information Systems (ICICIS)
DO  - 10.1109/icicis66182.2025.11313180
AB  - Environmental toxins interact with disease determinants in complex ways, requiring computational structures able to capture biological heterogeneity. Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) represent a promising conceptual framework to describe such complicated interplays. In our current research, we build a heterogeneous biomedical knowledge graph (KG) based on the Toxin and Toxin Target Database (T3DB) 1, containing 49,501 nodes and 89,988 edges which are toxins, symptoms, protein/gene targets, routes of exposure, and environmental factors. Our prediction task can be defined as a two-step procedure: we first apply node prediction to toxins using embeddings and then apply link-prediction methods in order to identify toxin-disease associations. This type of layered architecture makes it easier to extract shared nodes among the predicted links, thus enhancing both interpretability and biological relevance. Experimental assessments were done on an $80 / 20$ training test split, using a variety of random seeds to ensure robustness. Accuracy, precision, recall and F1-score were used as a measure of model evaluation. Findings highlight that Graph Attention Networks (GAT) have the best trade-off between accuracy and generalization, reaching an F1-score of 0.975; compared to RGCN and Enhanced GCN which is stable when faced with smaller or noisier graphs. The work has three main contributions: (1) incorporation of environmental exposure pathways into a toxin-disease KG, thus transcending the scope of a pure molecular toxicity prediction; (2) a systematic benchmark of a variety of GNNs within a systematic evaluation pipeline; and (3) the insights of interpretability, elucidating a variety of biologically meaningful substructures. Our proposed work highlights the critical nature of KG embeddings in combination with GNNs for predictive toxicology and environmental health analytics.
