AB  - To address the challenges of insufficient representation of exercise-knowledge concept relationships and difficulties in modeling long-range dependencies in Knowledge Tracing (KT), this paper proposes an innovative solution. First, a knowledge-weighted Q-matrix optimization method is designed: dynamically calculating weight proportions based on the difficulty of knowledge concepts, transforming binary relationships into continuous [0,1] interval representations to precisely capture association differences between exercises and concepts. Second, a Transformer-based deep knowledge tracing model integrating knowledge-weighted Q-matrix (KQTKT) is constructed to model long-range dependencies through a self-attention mechanism. Experimental validation demonstrates that this method significantly enhances relational representation capability and effectively improves prediction accuracy and interpretability. Results on four public benchmark datasets show that the KQTKT model achieves notable performance improvements over mainstream baseline models, with an average Area Under the Curve (AUC) increase of 1.49% to 2.31%. This study not only provides a novel and interpretable solution for modeling complex relationships in knowledge tracing but also establishes a solid technical foundation for building next-generation high-precision adaptive learning systems.
