AB  - Recent developments in sentiment analysis underline the necessity for models that mix deep learning with domain-specific expertise, especially for languages with few resources like Indonesian. By suggesting a hybrid architecture combining BERT with structured sentiment knowledge graphs, this work tackles the problem of aspect-based sentiment analysis (ABSA) in e-commerce reviews. The model uniquely addresses two important drawbacks: (1) the difficulty of pure data-driven techniques to use current sentiment lexicons and (2) the semantic distortion brought on by naive knowledge injection strategies. We propose three technical contributions: (1) a dynamic knowledge selection mechanism that retrieves relevant sentiment triples from the structured knowledge graph (SKG); (2) a sentence encoder with soft-position embeddings that retains sentence semantics; and (3) a masked self-attention mechanism to prevent information leakage from irrelevant nodes. With specific increases in recognizing implicit characteristics (+23% F1-score), the suggested design reaches 94.3% accuracy instead of 88.7% for traditional IndoBERT. Unlike conventional approaches, the model preserves interpretability using explicit aspect-sentiment mappings apparent in the attention weights. This work offers a useful model for improving ABSA systems in resource-constrained settings without calling for more labeled data.
