AB  - Knowledge graph completion (KGC) plays a pivotal role in addressing data incompleteness and inconsistency in domain-specific knowledge representations, particularly in safety-critical fields such as electrical power systems. This paper presents a novel hybrid model, termed EntityFusion-KGC (Entity Description Fusion–Knowledge Graph Completion), which integrates both textual semantic information and graph structural features to enhance KGC performance within the context of electrical safety applications. The proposed architecture encompasses four core components. First, an improved BERT-based encoding mechanism is developed to extract domain-specific semantic representations from unstructured entity descriptions. Second, graph topology is modeled using the TransE algorithm to capture latent relational features among entities. Third, a weighted fusion module, incorporating a graph attention network (GAT), adaptively aggregates semantic and structural embeddings by assigning dynamic importance weights. This fusion mechanism facilitates effective multi-source representation learning. Finally, the ENTITYFUSION-KGC model is empirically evaluated on a domain-curated electrical safety knowledge graph through comprehensive link prediction and entity classification experiments. Experimental results indicate that the model outperforms several benchmark methods in terms of Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR) and Hits@K metrics. The integration of enriched textual semantics and attention-guided structural features demonstrates a significant improvement in reasoning accuracy and robustness. The proposed model contributes a scalable and interpretable solution to enhance knowledge completion in electrical safety domains, with potential applicability in broader safety-critical knowledge systems.
