AB  - This paper aims to address the challenges of poor interpretability in data-driven models and the difficulty of quantitatively integrating expert knowledge in power equipment state estimation. It proposes a dual-channel adaptive fusion network based on a knowledge graph and temporal Transformer. The method processes vibration signals and load currents through a multimodal temporal encoder, uses conditional layer normalization for operational condition adaptive feature extraction, and incorporates expert knowledge as vector representations using a graph attention network. Finally, a gating fusion mechanism dynamically integrates data features and knowledge representations. Experimental results show that the proposed model achieves an accuracy of 98.5% and an F1 score of 97.8% on the test set, outperforming the best baseline model by 3.3%. Ablation experiments indicate that the knowledge fusion mechanism leads to a 2.4% improvement in accuracy and a 3.3% increase in the F1 score, with a 5.2% improvement in recall for "attention" class samples. Case diagnostics show that the model’s decision-making logic aligns closely with expert knowledge, and attention weights reveal the highest focus on key entities such as "light load" (0.34) and "overheated winding temperature" (0.28). This study confirms the effectiveness of the knowledge-enhanced strategy in power equipment state estimation and provides new insights into addressing the interpretability issues in data-driven models.
