DO  - 10.1109/cscloud66326.2025.00041
AB  - Smart grids generate heterogeneous data streams that span real-time operation and long-horizon planning. However, Transaction Processing (TP) data and Analytical Processing (AP) data differ markedly in timeliness, structure, and semantics, creating persistent barriers to end-to-end intelligence. We propose MGA-KGF, a multi-granularity, layered framework for knowledge-graph-centric fusion of heterogeneous multi-source smart-grid data. MGA-KGF (i) performs unified multi-source access and quality assurance, (ii) constructs fine-grained, mediumgrained, and coarse-grained knowledge units with explicit spatiotemporal alignment, and (iii) realizes bidirectional TP/AP fusion via an event-driven TransE-GAT pipeline with temporal and statistical attention. A load-aware storage and indexing scheme dynamically balances query latency and compression by migrating hot and cold knowledge. Deployed across core scenarios-equipment lifecycle management, rapid fault localization and traceability, regional load forecasting and resilience assessment, and O&M risk evaluation-MGA-KGF improves timeliness, semantic consistency, and cross-granularity reasoning quality, while remaining modular and extensible. The framework offers a practical path toward knowledge-reliable, real-time-toplanning integration in modern power systems and lays the groundwork for future incorporation of large language models and renewable-rich operating contexts.
