AB  - The synthesis of biomedicine and big data analysis came as one of the most important revolutions that transformed the contemporary health-care giants as complex patterns could now be discovered from overwhelming and heterogeneous large-scale datasets. Of these, clinical and multi-omics data i.e. genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics and metabolomics provide deep insight into disease mechanisms as well as patient stratification and personalized therapies. Nevertheless, the admixture and comprehension of such a high dimensional-scale data are still challenges in matter for volume, velocity, variety and veracity. Here, we present a scalable analytical pipeline that leverages big data infrastructure and machine learning algorithms to discover clinically interpretable patterns from integrated multi-omics and clinical datasets. The proposed system includes modular stages for data ingestion, preprocessing, normalization and feature selection, dimensionality reduction, and predictive modeling. The system is compatible with distributed computing platforms such as Apache Spark and Hadoop used to process petabyte-scale biomedical data at an unparalleled speed. It can accommodate multiple data formats and guarantee strong interoperability between structured clinical records, unstructured notes or omics profiles. The pipeline includes tools for bioinformatics and ontologies so that biological entities can be combined in clinical terms. Major innovations include the use of hybrid machine learning models (ensemble, deep neural networks and unsupervised clustering algorithms) for feature correlation analysis, disease classification and patient subtyping. The models are trained and validated on large-scale data such as biobanks, electronic health records (EHRs), and public repositories of patients such as TCGA and GTEx. A side note on dimensionality reduction methods Such as t-SNE, UMAP or PCA: these methods can be used to visualize and interpret the latent space of high-throughput 
