DO  - 10.1109/rivf68649.2025.11365038
AB  - Industrial systems generate large-scale multivariate time series (MTS) data from interconnected sensors. Discovering temporal causality is crucial for root cause analysis (RCA), forecasting anomaly propagation, and enabling explainable predictive maintenance. However, data-driven causal discovery methods often yield implausible or physically inconsistent causal relations when applied to complex industrial systems. Meanwhile, technical knowledge captured in schematics, component specifications, and operational manuals is rarely cross-validated against real operational data. We propose a hybrid framework that first applies Temporal Causal Discovery Framework (TCDF) to extract candidate causal relations, then verifies them against an industrial Knowledge Graph (KG), and finally integrates both into an interpretable Temporal Causal Graph (TCG). The refined TCG is embedded into a feature-level anomaly detection pipeline that combines Median Absolute Deviation (MAD) with dynamic Peak-Over-Threshold (POT). This enables fine-grained anomaly localization and causal explanation, moving beyond blackbox global alarms.
