AB  - Against the backdrop of digital transformation, issues such as metadata fragmentation, data silos, and low-quality data from inconsistent data standards across business systems have hindered the release of data value. However, traditional data lineage analysis methods struggle to meet precise governance needs due to high computational complexity, semantic understanding biases, and high implementation costs. To address these, we propose a multi-dimensional lineage identification framework integrating BERT-based domain semantic modeling, weighted Levenshtein dynamic programming edit distance, and quantitative analysis of table structure field intersections. The framework captures deep semantic associations between data entities via a domain-specific fine-tuned BERT model, optimizes table name matching accuracy using an edit distance algorithm with a common prefix compensation mechanism, and balances evaluation biases from field quantity differences by incorporating core field overlap metrics. Experimental results show this scheme significantly outperforms traditional methods in lineage relationship identification accuracy (F1-score of 95.38%) and cross-domain adaptability, providing a solution with theoretical innovation and engineering practicality for data traceability and quality control in metadata governance.
