AB  - Urdu has a complex linguistic structure. It has notable challenges for Natural Language Processing (NLP), especially in emoji prediction on platforms like Twitter. Despite emojis enhancing emotional expression globally, Urdu remains underexplored due to limited resources. This study addresses multi-label, multi-class emoji prediction using a large-scale dataset of 1 million Urdu tweets. This dataset labeled with both single and multiple emojis, covering 2,114 unique emojis. Sequential models like LSTM showed limitations in capturing long-range dependencies, while transformer-based models, particularly fine-tuned RoBERTa, offered better contextual understanding. We further introduce a novel Semantic Similarity-Based Emoji Prediction (SSEP) approach, combining word and emoji embeddings with Facebook AI Similarity Search (FAISS) to enhance semantic matching and retrieval. Comparative evaluation with English, Chinese, Hindi, and Arabic methods highlights the unique low-resource constraints of Urdu. Results demonstrate that transformer-based and semantic similarity methods outperform traditional models, with SSEP achieving the highest performance, establishing its effectiveness for emoji prediction in low-resource languages.
