AB  - This paper details the methods proposed by the BAMBOOVN team during their participation in the 5th Automated Legal Question Answering Competition (ALQAC 2025). During the competition we have to resolve two main tasks: Legal Document Retrieval and Legal Question Answering. For the Legal Document Retrieval task we applied an ensemble method: semantic searching with embedding outputs from BGE-M3 transformer model and traditional ranking methods using word information: BM25, TF-IDF supported by a topic classification model. After pre-ranking step we used a relevant classification model to grade the retrieved document as relevant or not relevant. These supportive models (topic/relevant classification) were trained by combining both original data and LLM-augmented data for better accuracy. The final score is combined using tuned hyperparameters and will be compared with an ensemble threshold to get filtered. For the Legal Question Answering task, we have three types of questions: true/false questions, multiple-choices question and free-text question. Suppose that the retrieved document from previous stage is correct, we address this problem by using Large Language Model (LLM) with prompt engineering technique to attain the generalization of LLM on the question answering task. While our approach did not attain the highest scores in the competition, it proved that using LLM-synthesized data within an adaptive pipeline (integrating LLMs with auxiliary models) effectively mitigates data scarcity limitations.
