AB  - Following its adoption in 2018, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) has impacted data processing entities significantly, especially by compelling them to ensure their privacy policies are compliant with a defined set of requirements. Manual assessment of GDPR compliance is laborious and susceptible to errors, driving increased research interest in automated solutions with such capabilities. This paper provides a systematic review of the recent advancements in the automated evaluation of privacy policies employing Natural Language Processing (NLP) methods. Within this context, this study proposes a structured approach for processing Romanian privacy policies, a particularly complex task, considering both the low-resource status of the Romanian language and the intricacy of the regulatory wording utilized. Aiming to address these constraints, this paper proposes a compliance verification system, leveraging the semantic similarity capabilities of the E5 Transformer model. Experimental results indicated that the trained model achieved a 75% accuracy in matching sentences extracted from a Romanian privacy policy to the appropriate GDPR requirements. Furthermore, the paper tackles the challenges of adapting NLP-based solutions to other languages with scarce resources, providing insights and directions for future research in multilingual and domain-specific settings.
