AB  - Legal professionals and judicial bodies often face the challenge of analyzing extensive legal documents, identifying applicable constitutional articles, and referring to relevant precedent. It is a time-consuming and inconsistent process. The core challenge of digital case records lies in automating legal analysis while maintaining accuracy, interpretability, and fairness. Traditional systems rely on rule-based or keyword-matching methods fail to understand the semantic depth of legal language. Additionally, retrieving precedent cases and aligning them with constitutional provisions demands a contextual understanding that static systems lack. Hence, this paper introduces an AI-powered legal analysis system that leverages deep learning and Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) to provide real-time legal judgment prediction and relevant case retrieval. The system employs Google Pegasus for abstractive legal text summarization, efficiently condensing complex case documents while preserving critical information and intent. The system architecture includes - Legal Text Summarization using Google Pegasus to generate concise representations of case details, Article Matching and Retrieval via RAG to identify applicable constitutional provisions, and Relevant Case Retrieval leveraging semantic embeddings to fetch past cases with contextual similarity. The key improvements include a significant reduction in manual workload, enhanced consistency in legal interpretations, and real-time generation of judgment reports. The integration of summarization, semantic matching, and intelligent retrieval ensures both accuracy and scalability. Hence, the system delivers a smart, scalable solution for automating legal analysis. It enhances judicial efficiency, supports fair decision-making, and empowers legal professionals with accurate AI-generated insights and paving the way for next-generation legal technology.
