AB  - Forecasting equity markets has traditionally relied on structured data sources, such as historical prices, fundamentals, and macroeconomic indicators. However, unstructured data, including analyst reports, earnings-call transcripts, and financial news, can provide valuable qualitative insights to enhance these forecasts. The proposed system employs a multi-stage pipeline that includes data ingestion, domain-specific text chunking, and dual-indexing (lexical and vector-based) to support hybrid retrieval. Four retrieval paradigms are evaluated—traditional text search, vector-based retrieval, hybrid retrieval, and vector-based retrieval with re-ranking—on a custom dataset of 315 financial documents, augmented by 20 control questions, and validated against the FinQA dataset. Experimental results, assessed via ROUGE metrics and expert evaluations, indicate that incorporating vectorization and re-ranking not only improves the precision of retrieved information but also enhances the contextual accuracy of LLM-generated responses. The findings demonstrate that SMART-Eq effectively bridges qualitative insights with quantitative data, offering a robust and scalable approach for enhanced equity market analysis and forecasting. The paper concludes with a discussion of integration challenges and future research directions, including domain-adapted LLM fine-tuning and real-time data processing.
