AB  - This research aims to design an automated system for monitoring and evaluating environmental document revisions, particularly in the context of Environmental Impact Analysis (EIA) and Environmental Management and Monitoring Efforts (UKL-UPL). This system leverages technologies such as natural language processing (NLP), optical character recognition (OCR), and document management to enhance the efficiency and accuracy of the document revision process. The system is divided into several stages: document uploading, text extraction from various formats using tools such as Apache Tika and PyMuPDF, feedback analysis through integration with Google Sheets, and text matching with semantic analysis using SBERT embeddings. The final evaluation is performed automatically and generates a report containing suggestions and feedback that have been completed. In the experimental results, five of eleven suggestions from the revised UKL-UPL documents were successfully detected as “Completed” with a similarity threshold of $\geqslant 0.75$. The remaining six suggestions showed lower similarity scores and were marked as “Not Completed.” This indicates that the system successfully identified some of the addressed suggestions, with potential for improvement in detection accuracy. Automating document revisions' evaluation ensures a more transparent, consistent, and reliable process, reducing manual errors and delays. This approach aligns with the growing need for digital solutions in environmental document management, enhancing operational efficiency and compliance with environmental regulations.
