TI  - IndoColSmol: Lightweight Vision-Language Models for Multimodal Indonesian Document Search
PY  - 2025
JO  - 2025 International Conference on Data Science and Its Applications (ICoDSA)
DO  - 10.1109/icodsa67155.2025.11157156
AB  - Recent progress in document retrieval increasingly leverages vision-language models that bypass OCR by jointly encoding both visual and textual content. These models capture layout, font, and image features typically ignored by text-only approaches. However, state-of-the-art architectures often require substantial computational resources, limiting their applicability in real-time or low-resource environments. Lightweight alternatives such as ColFlor and ColSmolVLM improve efficiency but are primarily trained on English corpora, resulting in reduced effectiveness in Indonesian settings. This work introduces IndoColSmol-256M and IndoColSmol-500M, two compact vision-language retrievers optimized for Indonesian document image collections. Based on the ColSmol architecture, both models apply a ColBERT-style late interaction mechanism, where each query and document is represented by multiple embeddings, and relevance is computed through fine-grained pairwise similarity between all query and document vectors. This strategy balances retrieval accuracy and computational efficiency. We perform contrastive fine-tuning on Indonesian image-query pairs, allowing the models to learn semantic alignment without relying on OCR or token-level supervision. Evaluation on the Indonesian Multimodal Open Question Answering (IMOQA) benchmark shows that IndoColSmol-256M and IndoColSmol-500M achieve Recall@5 scores of 0.88764 and 0.89045 respectively, outperforming multimodal baselines such as CLIP and SIGLIP. Both models offer low memory usage and inference latency, making them suitable for deployment in constrained environments such as mobile search, internal document lookup systems, and offline access tools. This study recommends further research on region-level alignment and multilingual training strategies to extend compact vision-language retrieval to additional low-resource languages and specialized document domains.
