DO  - 10.1109/mlbdbi67855.2025.11331503
AB  - Early detection of dyslexia in preschool children is critical for initiating interventions during the period of heightened neuroplasticity when literacy foundations are first established. However, existing screening technologies rely heavily on costly infrared-based eye trackers and specialized clinical expertise, thereby excluding resource-constrained educational contexts from benefiting from early diagnostic measures. This study proposes a scalable, low-cost dyslexia screening framework that integrates commodity webcams with advanced computer vision and machine learning pipelines, extracting fixation duration, regression frequency, saccadic amplitude, and dispersion entropy as predictive gaze features. A cohort of 428 preschoolers aged 4–6 years participated in controlled classroom-based tasks, generating over five million gaze events subsequently analyzed through logistic regression, random forests, and CNN-LSTM models with ensemble optimization. Results demonstrated that the proposed system achieved an AUC of 0.95 with CNN-LSTM and an accuracy of 86.3% with logistic regression, approaching the reliability of commercial devices while maintaining hardware costs below USD 50 per unit. Subgroup analysis confirmed robustness across age, gender, socio-economic strata, and bilingual participants, with regression frequency and fixation duration explaining the majority of predictive variance. The findings provide empirical evidence that webcam-based gaze analytics can offer equitable access to dyslexia screening, supporting large-scale adoption within public education systems.
