PY  - 2025
JO  - Proceedings of the 2025 3rd International Conference on Internet of Things and Cloud Computing Technology
DO  - 10.1145/3776865.3776921
AB  - Efficient and accurate matching between material specifications and price information is a key challenge in construction cost estimation. Manual comparison is inefficient and error-prone, while existing automated retrieval methods often rely on single-channel modeling or global fusion, failing to balance semantic understanding with precise field-level matching. This paper proposes an intelligent retrieval framework for construction material price information based on dual-channel hybrid semantic modeling. First, a large language model–driven query semantic enhancement mechanism performs semantic alignment and field explicitness, mitigating noise, abbreviations, and ambiguities in raw queries. Second, a field-aware fine-grained fusion mechanism separately computes dense and sparse similarities for fields such as material, specification, and unit, and adaptively balances semantic and exact matching at the field level. Finally, a field-level dynamic weight learning model adjusts the contribution of different fields according to query characteristics, ensuring stable identification of target records. Experiments on a real-world dataset demonstrate that our approach significantly outperforms single-channel methods and classical baselines in ({rm{Recall@K}} ) and ({rm{MRR}} ), particularly improving robustness on specification and unit matching. The proposed framework offers a low-cost, scalable, and domain-adaptive solution, enhancing the precision and intelligence of construction cost management.
KW  - dual-channel fusion, engineering material matching, query enhancement, semantic retrieval
