DO  - 10.1145/3748825.3748832
AB  - This paper proposes an intelligent piano education system (DM-LFTP) based on dynamic meta-learning and light-field haptic fusion, which achieves closed-loop control of multimodal perception, personalised decision-making and immersive interaction through a three-tier collaborative architecture. The system adopts Music Transformer to construct a music theory knowledge graph (2048 nodes, 15,360 edges), combines with Conditional Variational Auto-Encoder (CVAE) to realise melodic variation generation, and innovatively designs a dual-channel co-ordination mechanism based on the cosine similarity (ε=0.85), which reduces the potential spatial alignment error by 62.3%. The light-field haptic fusion system achieves sub-millimetre spatial mapping (localisation error &lt;0.4mm) and sub-millisecond haptic synchronisation (latency of 9.1ms) with the JVC D-ILA light-field engine (pixel pitch of 8.5μm) and 100\texttimes{}25 piezoelectric array, with a linearity of the light-intensity-tactile-force mapping function (T(I)=0.511-3 ) up to R2=0.97. The experimental results show that: (i) the dynamic meta-learning mechanism improves the touch-key recognition accuracy to 93.8% ( (Delta ) +3.7%, p&lt;0.001), and the rhythmic weighting steady state error is reduced by 73.4%; (ii) the light-field system achieves 256 depth samples at a refresh rate of 60Hz, with a crosstalk ratio of &lt;25dB; and (iii) the overall system latency is 11.4ms, which enhances the real-time teaching and learning by 40.2% compared with the traditional scheme. Clinical tests show that the trainees' fingering accuracy is improved by 32.7% (58.2%→90.9%), and improvisation ability is improved by 41.5% (MMI index 0.195→0.301N-s/m). A new technological paradigm is provided for the intelligentisation of music education.
KW  - haptic feedback, intelligent music education, light field display, meta-learning, multimodal fusion
