TI  - Multimodal Fusion of Gene Expression and Alternative Polyadenylation Profiles for Spatial Clustering
PY  - 2025
JO  - Proceedings of the 12th International Conference on Bioinformatics Research and Applications
DO  - 10.1145/3774976.3774990
AB  - Spatial transcriptomics technology facilitates the study of tissue cell function, microenvironment interactions, and disease pathogenesis by capturing spatial location and gene expression data. However, most existing spatial clustering methods primarily focus on integrating gene expression and spatial location information while ignoring the important alternative polyadenylation(APA) information. As a key mechanism of transcriptional regulation, APA increases transcriptomic complexity and enriches the features for clustering analysis. To address this limitation, we propose a multimodal spatial clustering method (MSC) that integrates gene expression data, APA information, and spatial location information to enhance clustering performance. Specifically, MSC constructs a percentage distal poly(A) site usage index (PDUI) matrix by identifying and quantifying poly(A) sites and imputing missing values. Subsequently, it combines multiple algorithms to select important gene features and employs regularized generalized canonical correlation analysis (RGCCA) algorithm to achieve efficient multimodal data fusion and spatial clustering. Experimental results on multiple spatial transcriptomics datasets demonstrate that MSC significantly outperforms existing methods in terms of the Adjusted Rand Index score and more accurately reconstructs spatial structures of tissues. This study not only highlights the critical role of APA information in spatial clustering but also provides new insights into gene regulation mechanisms and multimodal data integration.
KW  - Alternative polyadenylation, Feature selection, Multimodal clustering, Spatial transcriptomics
