AB  - Subgraph matching is a nonnegligible task in graph data analysis and has been widely applied in domains such as bioinformatics and computer vision. Owing to its NP-hard nature, most existing subgraph matching methods are forced to balance computational efficiency with matching accuracy, often compromising deep structural information in large-scale graphs. To handle this problem, this paper proposes an integrated model named Dynamic Multi-hop Attention Graph Neural Network (DyMA-GNN). In DyMA-GNN, the attention weights of neighboring nodes are dynamically assigned through an adaptive node weight learning mechanism, rather than fixed rules. Based on the adaptive mechanism, a dynamic multi-hop attention fusion framework is designed to hierarchically balance the initial features and multi-hop aggregated features, effectively capturing higher-order dependencies and long-range connections while preserving local structural information. In addition, a composite loss function optimization strategy is defined to effectively suppress the noise interference and enhance the robustness of the model. Experiments are conducted on real datasets from three different fields, achieving higher matching accuracy with less computational cost than the state-of-the-art baseline methods.
KW  - Subgraph matching, Graph neural network, Dynamic multi-hop attention, Composite loss function
