AB  - Data access traceability involves analyzing and tracking the access paths of data to identify data usage patterns and uncover potential issues. With the increasing complexity and scale of data access behaviors, traditional data access traceability methods face numerous challenges when dealing with large-scale and dynamically changing data access scenarios. These challenges include low traceability accuracy, low efficiency, and poor path interpretability.To address these issues, this paper proposes a novel approach for traceability of power grid fundamental data access by integrating graph embedding and path inference. Specifically, we construct a data access graph to capture the entities and relationships involved in data access. The graph embedding technique is employed to extract the structural and semantic information of the data access entities and relationships. Furthermore, path inference methods are combined to enhance the traceability of data access, thereby improving the interpretability of the traceability results.Experimental verification was conducted on simulated datasets, and the results showed that this method outperforms the comparison models Node2Vec-DRL, TransH, and RandomWalk in small, medium, and large-scale data access traceability graphs.Notably, the traceability accuracy remains above 90% in small-scale data access graphs, indicating a significant improvement in both traceability accuracy and interpretability. Our proposed method provides valuable theoretical and practical insights for the traceability of power grid fundamental data access.
KW  - Deep reinforcement learning, Path reasoning, graph embedding
