AB  - With the vigorous development of the new energy vehicle industry, the number and types of new energy vehicle parts are also increasing. In this context, it is particularly important to effectively analyze and identify new energy vehicle parts. This analysis not only helps to deepen the theory, but also provides support for practical applications, such as the research and development of new parts and supply chain management. In the analysis of new energy vehicle parts, named entity recognition plays a key role. It involves extracting key information such as part names, technical parameters and performance indicators from a large amount of text data such as technical documents, market reports, and supply chain information. This information is crucial for product development, market strategy formulation, and supply chain management. To meet this challenge, this paper proposes a LFRC (LLM+Fine-turning+Reflective-Chain-of-Thought) method to identify key information such as the names, technical parameters, and performance indicators of new energy vehicle parts. This method improves on the basic Chain-of-Thought and improves the task performance through a low-rank adaptive fine-tuning method. Experimental results show that the LFRC exhibits superior performance over multiple baselines with respect to critical metrics like recognition precision and retrieval rate.
