AB  - Image matching between image/object pairs is an active research and development domain. State-of-the-art (SOTA) Computer Vision-based and Deep Learning-based image matching models rely on global and/or local image features in a coarse-to-fine manner. Moreover, a fine-grained image matching framework is also introduced to break down objects into classes and subclasses. However, robustness and stability to time-varying and dynamic image changes in the real world remain unsolved. To this end, this paper has presented StructCon-ST for coarse-to-fine image matching between image and object pairs. It is the first time that a Large Vision model (LVM) with a novel Cross-Attention mechanism is presented to adapt visual-textual alignment to temporal context and ambient changes. A novel structure-based graph model/constraint is introduced to enhance the generalization of the loss function in LVM. Experimental results show a promising image matching model over SOTA models in accuracy.
